            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="https://www.zotero.org/groups/382445/items/I6XXZEB6">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><g ref="#menorah">&#x1f54e;</g>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name>Ἀττίν
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/>ις</name></persName> <choice><orig>βρε<supplied reason="omitted">σ</supplied>β
                    <lb n="4" break="no"/>ύτερο
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/>ς</orig><reg>πρεσβύτερος</reg></choice>
               </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#JP">
                <listApp><app><note>Text after Brugnone and photograph</note></app>
                    <app loc="3"><note>Brugnone: βρ&lt;ε&gt;σβ; lapis: βρϲβ, and since elsewhere lunate sigma is quadrate while epsilon is lunate, a weakly incised epsilon and omitted sigma seems more likely</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Attinis, (the) elder</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Presbuteros with initial B is also attested in <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003631">ISic003631</ref> (Siracusa). The inscription is for a member of the council of elders within the local jewish community. The form Attinis is not otherwise documented.
                    <!--epitaph of a member of the council of the elders, one Attinis (presbuteros). Attinis is an otherwise undocumented name, which Curbera concludes might be from Attinos or Attinas in a syncopated from from Attinios, a common Egyptian formation. C notes 'the scarcity of Latin names among Sicilian Jews'--></p>
            </div>
